As such, we need accurate location data, good photos, and - hopefully - some textual description of the habitat within which  you made your observation. Was is found in a preserve? A public park? project.title: Plants of Texas
project.description:
The purpose of this project is to broaden the understanding of Texas plant communities - both native and non-native - and contribute to knowledge of their diversity and range. It is hoped that the observations within this project will lead to a greater appreciation of the botanical Texas, while also helping guide resources toward conservation efforts.   

While this project was started by a citizen scientist and Texas Master Naturalist as a hobby project, we encourage the use of the project and data by research and conservation professionals working in all areas of Texas botany. Also, observations of Species of Greatest Conservation Need (SGCN) may be invited to other appropriate projects, such as the TPWD-curated project, Texas Botanical Treasures at http://www.inaturalist.org/projects/texas-botanical-treasures  so that conservation planning and resources can be directed at the plant community as needed. 

As such, we need accurate location data, good photos, and - hopefully - some textual description of the habitat within which  you made your observation. Was is found in a preserve? A public park? An urban or suburban setting? Is it in an area in danger of development? â€“ any information that may help inform understanding of the plant or its habitat.

project.title: Biodiversity of Texas: A Citizen-Science Project
project.description: The mission of the University of Texas' Texas Natural Science Center is "...to create awareness, understanding and appreciation of the past, present and future of biological diversity, especially that of the state of Texas." Since its establishment in 1936 (as the Texas Memorial Museum) it has done that via collection and preservation of specimens in its now large research collections. This project will help us further that mission, but now by adding photography and volunteers to our toolset. Observations contributed here will be curated and permanently archived by our curators and staff just as we have always done with specimens to assure that this project will fully complement our largely historic museum specimen-vouchered data and lead to a better understanding of the distribution, evolution, ecology and current status of the state's biodiversity.

project.title: Plants of Texas
project.description:
The purpose of this project is to broaden the understanding of Texas plant communities - both native and non-native - and contribute to knowledge of their diversity and range. It is hoped that the observations within this project will lead to a greater appreciation of the botanical Texas, while also helping guide resources toward conservation efforts.   

While this project was started by a citizen scientist and Texas Master Naturalist as a hobby project, we encourage the use of the project and data by research and conservation professionals working in all areas of Texas botany. Also, observations of Species of Greatest Conservation Need (SGCN) may be invited to other appropriate projects, such as the TPWD-curated project, Texas Botanical Treasures at http://www.inaturalist.org/projects/texas-botanical-treasures  so that conservation planning and resources can be directed at the plant community as needed. 

As such, we need accurate location data, good photos, and - hopefully - some textual description of the habitat within which  you made your observation. Was is found in a preserve? A public park? An urban or suburban setting? Is it in an area in danger of development? â€“ any information that may help inform understanding of the plant or its habitat.

project.title: Biodiversity of Texas: A Citizen-Science Project
project.description: The mission of the University of Texas' Texas Natural Science Center is "...to create awareness, understanding and appreciation of the past, present and future of biological diversity, especially that of the state of Texas." Since its establishment in 1936 (as the Texas Memorial Museum) it has done that via collection and preservation of specimens in its now large research collections. This project will help us further that mission, but now by adding photography and volunteers to our toolset. Observations contributed here will be curated and permanently archived by our curators and staff just as we have always done with specimens to assure that this project will fully complement our largely historic museum specimen-vouchered data and lead to a better understanding of the distribution, evolution, ecology and current status of the state's biodiversity.

project.description: The mission of the University of Texas' Texas Natural Science Center is "...to create awareness, understanding and appreciation of the past, present and future of biological diversity, especially that of the state of Texas." Since its establishment in 1936 (as the Texas Memorial Museum) it has done that via collection and preservation of specimens in its now large research collections. This project will help us further that mission, but now by adding photography and volunteers to our toolset. Observations contributed here will be curated and permanently archived by our curators and staff just as we have always done with specimens to assure that this project will fully complement our largely historic museum specimen-vouchered data and lead to a better understanding of the distribution, evolution, ecology and current status of the state's biodiversity.

taxon.name: Linum
taxon.wikipedia_summary: Linum (flax) is a genus of approximately 200 species in the flowering plant family Linaceae. They are native to temperate and subtropical regions of the world. The genus includes the common flax (L. usitatissimum), the bast fibre of which is used to produce linen and the seeds to produce linseed oil.
